@book{Mintzberg1973,
abstract = {(Review - Link below) Henry Mintzberg is the Roger Barker of the Executive Suite. Just as Barker (1 968) induced behavior setting theory from intensive observation of a handful of Kansans, Mintzberg induces a theory of managerial work from intensive observa- tion of a handful of executives. And just as Barker's work shows the ecological invalidity of some of our most cherished concepts, Mintzberg's work edits the organizational concepts we champion. Rarely has the field of organizational behavior had better evidence of the value of description and induction than is found in Mintzberg's book. And that's surprising, because his data base is mundane. Mintzberg watched five managers, each for one week, and recorded their verbal contacts, phone calls, and handling of mail in chronological order. And that's it. But, as is often the case, bland counting can be conceptually rich. Mintzberg certainly had no shortage of items on which to base his inductions. His five executives studied 659 pieces of incoming mail and generated 231 additional pieces of mail, all of which they interspersed between 368 verbal contacts. Mintzberg then categorized the purpose of each of these 1258 items and then collapsed these purposes into a set of ideas about the characteristics and the content of managerial work. The distinction between characteristics and content is a crucial one. Characteristics include things like where managers work, how long they work, at what pace they work and what media they use to do their work. Characteristics involve the context, the trappings, and the nature of the manager's work flow. This kind of information has been obtained by investiga- tors other than Mintzberg, most notably by those people (for instance, Stewart, Carlson) who had managers keep diaries. Unfortunately, what the diaries don't show is the actual content of what the manager does. The reason is simple. You've got to know in advance what people do if you want them to keep track of the f